  "texts": [
    "This human intervention into the computational process of response generation suggests that neither the machine nor the human is sufficient on its own.",
    "While, of course, an individual human's knowledge is limited and finite and thus could never produce results like an LLM, LLMs are also limited in that they must be trained by humans in order to produce answers that sound plausibly \"human.\"",
    "This creates a recursive process whereby humans first build and train LLMs and are subsequently taught and trained by them.",
    "The result is AI-generated text that reads to many users as though it were written by another human, while conveying encyclopedic knowledge on any given topic.",
    "Notably, LLMs can also respond to prompts or inputs written in natural language rather than in search terms."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}